\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \strokec2 Unoptimized JavaScript and Cascading Style Sheets create render-blocking bottlenecks, preventing the browser from painting the visible portion of the page until massive, often unnecessary, code files are fully parsed. The source code must undergo aggressive minification, a process that strips all unnecessary characters, line breaks, and developer comments from the HTML, CSS, and JS files, significantly reducing their overall payload size.
\fs19\fsmilli9600 \cf4 \super \strokec4 17
\f3\fs24 \cf0 \nosupersub \strokec3 \

\f2\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \strokec2 To achieve optimal First Contentful Paint scores, the critical CSS required to style the above-the-fold content must be extracted and inlined directly into the document head. This allows the browser to render the initial screen instantaneously. Simultaneously, all non-essential JavaScript, such as third-party analytics trackers, social media widgets, or complex calculator logic, must be deferred or loaded asynchronously so they do not interrupt the primary rendering path.
\fs19\fsmilli9600 \cf4 \super \strokec4 13
